\_\_NOTOC\_\_ We will need to analyze the linearized system at each
critical point.

\subsubsection{At \emph{(x,y) = (0,0)}}\label{at-xy-00}

\begin{align*}
J = \begin{pmatrix}3 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

which has eigenvectors $(1,0)^T$ and $(0,1)^T$ with corresponding
eigenvalues 3 and 1 respectively. The local solution structure centred
at (0,0) is

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} = C_1 \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} e^{3t} + C_2 \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} e^t
\end{align*}

Along both eigenvectors, the trajectories move away, with the $(1,0)^T$
direction being dominant, since it is multiplied by the larger term,
\emph{e\textsuperscript{3t}}.

\subsubsection{At \emph{(x,y) = (0,1)}}\label{at-xy-01}

\begin{align*}
J = \begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\ 1 & -1 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

To find the eigenvector corresponding to $\lambda = 2$, we seek the
solution to $(J - 2 I) \vec{v} = \vec{0}$ so that

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 1 & -3 \end{pmatrix} \vec{v} = \vec{0}
\end{align*} Or
$v_1 - 3v_2 = 0$, so we take $\vec{v} = (3,1)^T$.

To find the eigenvector corresponding to $\lambda = -1$, we seek the
solution to $(J - (-1) I) \vec{v} = \vec{0}$ so that

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \vec{v} = \vec{0}
\end{align*} Or
\emph{v\textsubscript{1} = 0}, \emph{v\textsubscript{2} = anything}, so
we take $\vec{v} = (0,1)^T$.

The local solution structure centred at (0,1) is

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} = C_1 \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} e^{2t} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} e^{-t}
\end{align*}

The solution grows exponentially along the $(3,1)^T$ direction and
decays exponentially along the $(0,1)^T$ direction. Starting anywhere
other than along the $(0,1)^T$ vector, the solution will approach the
$(3,1)^T$ vector.

\subsubsection{At \emph{(x,y) = (3,0)}}\label{at-xy-30}

\begin{align*}
J = \begin{pmatrix} -3 & -3 \\ 0 & 4 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

To find the eigenvector corresponding to $\lambda = -3$, we seek the
solution to $(J - (-3) I) \vec{v} = \vec{0}$ so that

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}0 & -3 \\ 0 & 7 \end{pmatrix} \vec{v} = \vec{0}
\end{align*} Or
\emph{v\textsubscript{2} = 0}, \emph{v\textsubscript{1} = anything}, so
we take $\vec{v} = (1,0)^T$.

To find the eigenvector corresponding to $\lambda = 4$, we seek the
solution to $(J - 4 I) \vec{v} = \vec{0}$ so that

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}-7 & -3 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \vec{v} = \vec{0}
\end{align*} Or
$-7 v_1 - 3v_2 = 0$, so we take $\vec{v} = (-3,7)^T$.

The local solution structure centred at (3,0) is

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} = C_1 \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} e^{-3t} + \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix} e^{4t}
\end{align*}

The solution grows exponentially along the $(-3,7)^T$ direction and
decays exponentially along the $(1,0)^T$ direction. Starting anywhere
other than along the $(1,0)^T$ vector, the solution will approach the
$(-3,7)^T$ vector.

\subsubsection{At \emph{(x,y) = (1,2)}}\label{at-xy-12}

\begin{align*}
J = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\ 2 & -2 \end{pmatrix},
\end{align*} which as we saw
in part (a) has complex eigenvalues with negative real part. By plugging
in a point, say $(1,0)^T$ into the local linear system we can determine
the direction of the spiral.

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\ 2 & -2 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

which points up and to the left at (1,0). Therefore the spiral is
counterclockwise.

This is all put together in the very rough global phase portrait.

